# ChainGrant — Hackathon Pitch Deck

---

## Slide 1 — Problem Statement

**Title:** The Broken Promise of Grants

**Points:**
- 💸 **₹1,200 Crore+** in student grants go untracked every year in India
- No visibility for sponsors — money is transferred and disappears
- Students have no proof of honest delivery of milestones
- Middlemen, delays, and fraud are rampant in traditional grant systems
- No immutable record exists when sponsors and students dispute outcomes

**Visual idea:** Split screen — Sponsor asking "Did they complete the work?" vs Student asking "Where is my payment?"

---

## Slide 2 — Solution

**Title:** ChainGrant — Trustless Grant Funding on the Blockchain

**Key message:** We replace trust with cryptographic proof.

**How:**
- Every grant is locked in a **smart contract escrow** on Algorand
- Funds are **only released** when the sponsor verifies the student's proof of work
- Every transaction is permanently recorded on-chain — visible to anyone
- Students earn **NFT badges** as on-chain reputation for every completed milestone

**Tagline:** _"Not a promise. A smart contract."_

---

## Slide 3 — Implementation

**Title:** How It Works — End to End

**Flow (step by step):**

1. 🔐 **Sponsor signs up** with email + Pera Wallet (wallet = identity)
2. 📋 **Sponsor creates a grant** — defines milestones, amounts, student wallet → funds locked in Algorand escrow smart contract
3. 📤 **Student submits proof** — uploads work description + generates a SHA-256 proof hash stored on-chain
4. ✅ **Sponsor approves** — triggers [release_funds](file:///c:/Users/Computar/Desktop/grant/smart-contract/contract.py#86-108) ABI call → payment sent directly to student's wallet via inner transaction
5. 🏅 **Student mints NFT Badge** — Algorand Standard Asset (ASA) minted as on-chain achievement credential
6. 🔍 **Public Transparency Wall** — all grants publicly viewable with Lora Explorer verification links

---

## Slide 4 — Tech Stack

**Title:** Built With Battle-Tested Web3 Infrastructure

| Layer | Technology |
|---|---|
| **Blockchain** | Algorand Testnet |
| **Smart Contract** | PyTeal / Puya Python (ARC-4 ABI) |
| **Wallet Auth** | Pera Wallet (QR + Mobile) |
| **Frontend** | React + TypeScript + Vite |
| **Styling** | Tailwind CSS + Framer Motion |
| **Database** | Firebase Firestore (metadata) |
| **NFT Standard** | Algorand Standard Assets (ASA) |
| **Contract Interface** | ARC-56 App Spec JSON |
| **Block Explorer** | Lora by Algokit |

**Key design decision:** Hybrid architecture — Firebase for speed, Algorand for immutability and trust.

---

## Slide 5 — Features

**Title:** What Makes ChainGrant Different

| Feature | Traditional Grants | ChainGrant |
|---|---|---|
| Fund custody | Bank / middleman | Smart contract escrow |
| Payment trigger | Manual / paper | On-chain ABI call |
| Proof of work | Email / document | SHA-256 hash stored on-chain |
| Transparency | Zero | Public Transparency Wall |
| Student credentials | Paper certificate | NFT badge on Algorand |
| Dispute resolution | Legal / slow | Smart contract enforces rules |
| Login | Username + password | Pera Wallet (Web3 native) |

**Bonus features:**
- 🔗 Every transaction links to Lora Explorer for public verification
- 🛡️ Only the registered sponsor can release funds (enforced by smart contract)
- 📊 Real-time dashboard for both sponsors and students

---

## Slide 6 — Conclusion

**Title:** The Future of Transparent, Trustless Funding

**What we built:**
- A fully functional grant management platform on Algorand Testnet
- Smart contract with ABI-encoded milestones, proof hash storage, and escrow logic
- Wallet-first authentication — your Pera Wallet IS your identity
- On-chain NFT reputation badges for students

**Impact:**
- Eliminates fraud in grant disbursement
- Gives sponsors real-time verifiable proof of milestone completion
- Creates a portable, on-chain reputation for students

**What's next:**
- Mainnet deployment
- Multi-milestone concurrent grants
- DAO-based grant approval for community-funded scholarships

> **"We don't ask you to trust us. We ask you to trust the code."**

